Zephides

On january 22, 2010
AndySQdancer
RobertP227, for the attackers grouping is the same, you group your dinoz and you control their moves. For the defenders, the game does the grouping. For the first attack, the 1st 5 of the 15 defenders that are alive are group to defend the castle. Then, the next attack, again it is the 1st 5 defenders that are alive that are grouped (any dinoz killed during the previous attack of course are excluded). Certain members of the clan have the right to order the 15 defenders that are defending the castle. Initially, the order is in the order in which their masters chose them to defend the castle. This is then modified by the clan members that have the rights to change the order of the defenders.

Good luck in your first war.

Hope I answered your question.

So here's what I'm seeing with the new scoring system.

Saturday and Sunday we won many wars, and this gave us a good boost in reputation. Monday we had 213 reputation, meaning opponents who had defeated us once could come back - and they did.

The resulting costly losses sent us back under 200 reputation - a significant decline - and it appears to have had a similar effect on others in roughly the same place that we are.

So this new scoring system will simply underline the clan class system. We, Axie Force, are part of the new "Middle Class", and the chips are stacked such that, if we try hard again, we will just be punished right back to where we are now.

so where do you get PWIN and PLOST
PWIN is the sum of the reputation of the clans over whom you have won.

PLOST is the reputation points you have lost to others in war.


In FETE's case:

PWIN: 7376 (calculated in the war tab)
PLOST: 413 x 4 = 1652 (lost 413 rep to BBCx2, EC, Dinotopia)

After your result, you have to take into consideration rep points lost by having your castle down.

Druid you got me wrong there.

For example lets take a very basic element of any RPG - the attack/damagesystem. All those Attack/Defense numbers which DinoRPG provides us are nearly useless when there is elementdefense involved. The attacksystem is nothing secret like double skills or new maps which we have fun to explore it. The attacksystem is always there its nothing new, nobody would ever have fun writing down 10 000 attacks and asking their enemies for their defense to somehow get a rough understanding of how it works.
You see the differences im trying to point out?
There are things that are given from the start, like the attacksystem, attackorder, skills etc. This is supposed to be your "safe place" we could also call it basic conditions. The randomness in here should be clearly recognizeable, so that you can estimate what scenarios may happen if do action A or action B.
From this "safe place" you start to explore new things such as maps, enemies, items (hi napodino ). You know exactly that unforseen things may happen and u try to make them less bad for u by configuring ur safe place to its optimum.
BUT if your safe place is unrecognizeable random itsself then u cant blame ur ursself for things that are happening, u will blame an "upper might" for your misfortune or the fortune of others and this leaves a feeling of unfairness in the players, which is bad.

The other difference what i want to point out is that there are things you can figure out by trial and error
but other things you wont ever be able to figure out unless u r some smart*ss mathematician and write down about 10 000 events and make an analysis.

And exactly those things which are...
a) in your safe place AND
b) you are not able to figure out by trial and error after a reasonable amount of time
-> those things i want to know.

- The attacksystem/damagesystem
- the clarification if its random or not that Sphere Skills affecting the triggerchance of normal skills (as u see i dont want know the exact triggerrate i just want to know if its random or not, so i can recognize it)
- and considering wars, the calculation of repuation

This things are all in my "safe place" or lets call them basic conditions, from what i try to found my actions on. Also those things cant be figured out without the help of developers in a reasonable amount of time.




Coming back to my example of the Pen&Paper games. They work exactly in that way. You are fully aware of the basic conditions. If there is randomness those conditions, you can clearly recognize them.


Btw, any game that will become "a math-based optimizing game" after the basic conditions being clarified is a bad game to begin with.
Good games try to balance the skills, races etc so any individual is able to materialize his likes and dislikes into a charakter/race/dino/team, thus making any constellation as unique as the player himself is and thus not making the game boring.

DinoRPG is good game, it has alot of variations and will be still fun to play, when players become full aware of their "safe place"
